deck: Wardell Chambers was a former mercenary partner of Deathstroke, and was behind the kidnapping of his daughter, Rose.
description: Wardell Chambers was a former mercenary partner of Slade Wilson. After his presumed death, Wardell was captured by the enemy and tortured. He was eventually infused with meta-human blood, which gave him the power to control the minds of others. He used his newfound power to escape, and began developing a plan to seek revenge on Slade, who he believed left him for dead.

description:
Origin

A crime lord with a one million dollar price on his head.

Creation

Written by Mark Waid and drawn by Lee Weeks.

Major Story Arcs

Almadovar learns that Interpol has infiltrated his building. He gets the jump on one of their agents, Sean Cassidy (Banshee), and nearly kills him. Deadpool arrives, however, and kills Almadovar first.
name: Almadovar

deck: Sharpshooter and brief Suicide Squad recruit
description:
Origin

The son of poor parents, raised in Gotham's Narrows, Will Evans was orphaned as a child when stray bullets from nearby gang violence flew through his house, killing his parents and sister but leaving him remarkably untouched. Vowing to seek revenge and to never waste a bullet, he began training as a sharpshooter and working as muscle for hire for criminal organisations. Becoming a criminal in Gotham, he briefly met Deadshot in prison; Deadshot later appropriated Evans' origin for himself. Some time later, having made a name for himself as an assassin, he was approached by Amanda Waller, who was seeking a replacement for Deadshot and invited him to join the Suicide Squad.

Creation

Will Evans was created by Brian Buccellato and Viktor Bogdanovic. He made his first appearance in Suicide Squad Most Wanted: Deadshot and Katana #1.

Major Story Arcs

Most Wanted

Evans is sent on a mission with Deadshot, to whom he takes an instant, and reciprocated, dislike. The pair attempt to capture the child of a ruthless drug lord, but the plan goes south when Deadshot abandons Evans. Taking matters into his own hands, Evans goes against orders and begins killing all of the people in the complex. He successfully completes the mission and accompanies Amanda Waller and several members of the Squad to track down Deadshot. He shoots the surrendering Deadshot several times, and takes the identity of Deadshot for himself. Joining the team for his first mission as Deadshot, he immediately goes rogue, abandoning mission objectives and assassinating several members of the Squad in the process. Attempting to take up the mantle of Deadshot as an assassin, he is frustrated to discover that the real Deadshot still lives. He kidnaps Lawton's daughter, Suchin, to lure Lawton into a deadly competition to determine which of them is the best. Predictably, he loses the fight, and is killed when Deadshot shoots him in the face.

Powers and Abilities

Evans has no known superhuman powers or abilities. He is a expert marksman, and skilled in the use of firearms. He is athletic, and in good physical condition.

Weapons and Equipment

Evans wears body armour modelled on that of Deadshot, which protects him from many forms of injury. He also wears a helmet modelled on Deadshot's, with a scope over his eye to aid in targeting and to enhance his senses. He carries two pistols, as well as a sniper rifle.

For reasons never stated Crom, his sister Lalla, and his pure iron sword Skull-cracker wander into Europe where over the course of a few adventures he becomes the ruler of Ophir with Queen Tanit.

Crom may be the first character from the sword & sorcery sub-genre to make it into the comics.

deck: An artificial construct designed to protect the Terranometer, Yologarch is based on four of the most prominent villains of the Marvel Universe
description:
Origin

Designed by Nikola Tesla, the Yologarch was built as an artificial intelligence program. The computer interface would lure powerful beings to the Terranometer, then expel the intruders after making a digital copy of the interloper. At the time of its modern day discovery, the templates of Loki, Doctor Doom, Ultron, and the Red Skull were stored.

Creation

Yologarch was created by Jeff Parker, Carlo Pagulayan, Ray-Anthony Height, and Wellington Alves. Its first appearance was in Red She-Hulk #65 (July 2013).

Red She-Hulk: Route 616

During their road trip mission, Red She-Hulk and Machine Man were drawn to Mount Rushmore. Exploring the monument, the heroes stumbled upon the powerful world computer known as the Terranometer. Sensing intruders, the A.I. activated its defense program to battle in both the physical and digital realms. Betty Ross confronted electronic duplicates of Ultron, Loki, Red Skull, and Doctor Doom while X-51 interacted with the computer itself. When Ross emerged victorious, the distinct personality templates merged into a solitary construct that dubbed itself Yologarch. Once again engaging She-Hulk, Yologarch finally overcame its intended programming. Fleeing the scene, the artificial intelligence vowed vengeance on Ross and the Terranometer's creators.
name: Yologarch
